over a two-decade period-shows that press reports most frequently cite the views of environmental activists as if they were the views of the scientific community. These findings cast doubt on the objectivity of the news media and environmental activists. And, the authors conclude, misplaced fears about the risks of environmental cancer have seriously distorted public policy and priorities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCancerxEnvironmental aspects. 0aCancerxPolitical aspects. 0aEnvironmentalism. 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh1 aRothman, Stanley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030007306540uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014858940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300148589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300148589/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY